properties.Title: Update: High Water Advisory Alert For Portions Of The Red River
properties.Summary:
Description: Update: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a High Water Advisory for the Red River at Ste. Agathe, the Red River Floodway Inlet Control Structure, and within the City of Winnipeg due to expected high flows. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions by the local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.
Expires: 2019-10-28T10:45:00-05:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Manitoba Emergency Measures Organization, 2019-10-27T10:52:36-05:00, 0EA7AC08-FEB9-4BD7-FDE4-0675F669638A
Area: The Red River at Ste. Agathe, the Red River Floodway Inlet Control Structure, and within the City of Winnipeg
properties.Author: Manitoba Emergency Measures Organization

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected. A strong low pressure system will bring damaging winds, with gusts near 100 km/h, to Paulatuk, Sachs Harbour, and Ulukhaktok later today. These winds will create blizzard conditions in Paulatuk beginning near noon today. Similar conditions will develop in Sachs Harbour and Ulukhaktok late this afternoon or early this evening. These blizzard conditions will improve overnight tonight into Tuesday morning as the wind weakens. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 6 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NTStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-29T02:43:35-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-28T10:44:35-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.0275129993.2019
Area: Sachs Harbour, Ulukhaktok, Paulatuk
properties.Author: Environment Canada

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A low pressure system approaching from the west will pass south of the Maritimes tonight and Monday. Over northwestern New Brunswick a mixture of rain and snow tonight will taper to showers or flurries by early Monday morning. Snowfall amounts of 2 to 5 centimetres are forecast especially over higher terrain. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NBStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-28T14:08:47-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-28T01:31:47-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.1848976776.2019
Area: Woodstock and Carleton County, Stanley - Doaktown - Blackville Area, Edmundston and Madawaska County, western half of Restigouche County, Campbellton and eastern half of Restigouche County, Grand Falls and Victoria County, Mount Carleton - Renous Highway

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. Strong winds, heavy snow and blowing snow over southern Kivalliq today and tonight. An intense low pressure system over western Hudson Bay is bringing strong northerly winds, heavy snow and blowing snow to the region which will persist throughout the day and tonight. Winds gusting at times to between 90 and 110 km/h will create near blizzard conditions at times today. Winds will diminish slightly tonight and continue to moderate on Tuesday. Total snowfall accumulations from this system will be in the 15 to 30 cm range. Conditions will improve on Tuesday ### Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-29T00:23:10-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-28T08:24:10-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.4182119726.2019
Area: Arviat, Rankin Region including Whale Cove, Chesterfield Inlet
properties.Author: Environment Canada

properties.Title: Snow Squall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls are expected. Under the snow squall bands, visibilities will be significantly reduced due to the heavy snow, and snow will quickly accumulate. Cold northwest winds blowing off Lake Winnipeg are generating snow squalls near Berens River, with localized accumulations up to 15 cm possible. The snow squalls should begin weakening this morning. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-28T16:59:37-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-28T09:39:37-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.1094819427.2019
Area: Berens River, Bloodvein
properties.Author: Environment Canada

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. Strong winds, heavy snow and blowing snow today and tonight improving on Tuesday. A low pressure system tracking across Hudson Bay is bringing strong northerly winds and heavy snow to the Churchill area. North winds will reach 70 gusting 90 km/h early this morning but diminish somewhat this afternoon and early this evening. Visibilities will be greatly reduced at times due to heavy snow and blowing snow, especially this morning. Winds may reintensify again overnight night before diminishing again Tuesday afternoon. Total snowfall accumulations are expected to be in the 15 to 20 cm range by Tuesday evening. Conditions will start to improve Tuesday as the system slowly weakens. ### Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-29T01:31:13-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-28T09:32:13-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.1977897470.2019
Area: Churchill
properties.Author: Environment Canada

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. A strong low pressure system which is giving heavy snow to areas along the Hudson Bay coast will also affect Baker Lake but mainly just with strong winds. Very strong northerly winds of 70 gusting 90 km/h are expected today and tonight before gradually moderating on Tuesday. ### Damage to buildings, such as to roof shingles and windows, may occur. Loose objects may be tossed by the wind and cause injury or damage. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.
Expires: 2019-10-29T00:28:49-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-10-28T08:29:49-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.0307370257.2019
Area: Baker Lake
